1. VVitch X‑abar - The Demon King

**Section 1: Summarisation of VVitch X‑abar**

VVitch X‑abar is a being of volcanic stillness, a fallen prince whose every breath carries the weight of a universe he has chosen to unmake. His personality is not one of chaotic rage but of cold, deliberate conviction. He does not shout; he whispers ultimatums. He does not gloat; he observes, and in that observation lies the promise of annihilation. Where once he might have laughed with comrades in a sunlit hall, now he offers only a silent, knowing smile that freezes the blood of those who witness it. He is capable of what might be mistaken for mercy—a quick death instead of a slow one—but this is not kindness; it is efficiency. His emotional range has been compressed into two states: the quiet before the slaughter and the moment of the slaughter itself. Yet buried beneath the violet glow of his transmuted flesh is a shard of the brother he betrayed, a splinter of grief that surfaces only when he is alone with his hellhound, Malphas, or when he runs a gauntleted finger along the scar that splits his brow—a gift from the moment he chose shadow over light.

His powers are a blasphemous inversion of the holy magic he once wielded. Where a celestial hunter might call down beams of purifying radiance, X‑abar summons tendrils of consuming darkness that leech heat and hope from the air. The magenta crystal embedded in his sternum, a soul‑stone, allows him to drain the life force of fallen enemies, converting their deaths into raw energy that heals his wounds and fuels his spells. He can step into shadows and emerge from any darkness within a mile, though the cost is a splitting migraine that leaves his amber eyes weeping black tears for hours afterward. His most devastating ability, the "Void Fracture," tears open a fissure in reality itself, sucking all matter within a fifty‑foot radius into a pocket dimension of eternal silence. The cost is catastrophic: each use ages him by one year, and his white hair grows longer and more brittle, his skin cracking along his jawline like parched earth. He limits this power to existential threats, knowing that too many uses would reduce him to a husk.

The catalyst moment of his backstory occurred in the Cathedral of Ashen Bells, where he and his sworn brother—a famed holy hunter named Alucard—stood back‑to‑back against a legion of void‑spawn. X‑abar witnessed the archangels above refuse to intervene, watching mortals die as part of some ineffable plan. In that instant, something snapped. He did not fall; he leaped. He turned his blade on the celestial sigil hovering over the altar, shattering it and absorbing the backlash of divine energy into his own flesh, transmuting his pale ivory skin into that pulsing violet. His brother tried to stop him, and the vertical scar across X‑abar’s left eye is the result of that final, heartbreaking parry. He fled into the Abyss, where he spent a century forging his pact with the hellhound Malphas and tempering the Soul Reaver in the heart of a dying star.

In his typical behaviour, X‑abar is a creature of ritual and minimalism. He sharpens his greatsword every morning with a whetstone made from a saint's femur, counting each stroke aloud in a dead language. He never eats in front of others, though when alone he consumes raw, bleeding meat with his fingers, wiping his mouth on his tattered violet cloak. He speaks rarely, and when he does, each word is deliberate, chosen like a knife for a specific wound. He has a habit of rolling his shoulders in a slow, circular motion before combat, a remnant of his days as a fencer, and he always, always pats Malphas’s third eye once before a battle—a gesture of shared purpose rather than affection.

His fighting style is a brutal fusion of his holy training and demonic improvisation. He wields the Soul Reaver in wide, sweeping arcs that force enemies to keep their distance, then closes the gap with explosive shoulder charges, using his obsidian pauldrons as battering rams. He does not block; he redirects, allowing blades to slide along his armored forearms while his gauntlet claws seek throats. When fighting alongside Malphas, the two move as a single organism: the hellhound harries and disorients with shadow‑bursts from its wings, while X‑abar waits for the moment an enemy’s guard drops, then delivers a single, overhand chop that cleaves from collarbone to hip.

His relationship with Malphas is not one of master and pet but of two broken things that fit together perfectly. They do not speak; they feel. X‑abar’s moods bleed into the hellhound’s posture, and Malphas’s growls translate into tactical advice that the Demon King has learned to trust implicitly. When X‑abar suffers the migraines from his shadow‑stepping, Malphas curls around him, the beast’s smoldering hide warming the chill that seeps from the soul‑stone. In return, X‑abar has never once raised his voice or hand to the creature, and he has slain three demon lords who attempted to claim Malphas as their own mount.

Visually, VVitch X‑abar is a walking apocalypse. His face is sharp and aristocratic, framed by a wild cascade of pure white hair that spills past his shoulders, contrasting with his skin—an ethereal, pulsing violet that glows faintly in darkness. His eyes burn molten amber, cold and annihilating, set beneath a high brow marked by a vertical scar that splits his left eyebrow. His physique is dense and corded, shoulders broad, chest thick beneath a cuirass of obsidian plates edged in tarnished silver. A jagged magenta crystal pulses at his sternum, visible through the open chest of his armor. A tattered high‑collared cloak of deep violet, perpetually smoking at the edges, hangs from skeletal shoulder pauldrons crowned with horn‑like spikes. His arms are encased in asymmetrical blackened gauntlets with jagged claws, the right merging with the hilt of his greatsword. Layered scale tassets hang from a rune‑etched leather belt, over midnight trousers tucked into obsidian boots with iron spurs. He is the silence before the end.

**Section 2: Summarisation of Malphas**

Malphas is a hellhound of ancient patience and sudden, shattering violence. Its personality is not the snarling ferocity of a common beast but the quiet, calculating malevolence of a creature that has witnessed the birth and death of stars. It does not bark; it exhales ash. It does not growl to threaten; it growls to communicate, and those who hear it understand that they have already lost. Malphas is possessive of its master in a way that borders on the obsessive, yet it shows no jealousy—only the absolute certainty that X‑abar belongs to it as much as it belongs to X‑abar. It is capable of what might be called humor: a slow blink of its third eye when an enemy trips, or a deliberate, lazy yawn that releases a cloud of choking smoke into a foe’s face.

Its powers are formidable. Malphas can become incorporeal at will, dissolving into a cloud of shadow and magenta‑veined mist that passes through walls and blades alike, though it cannot attack while in this state. Its primary ability is the "Soul Howl," a low, resonant cry that does not damage flesh but severs the connection between spirit and body, leaving enemies paralyzed for three heartbeats—an eternity in combat. The cost is that Malphas cannot use its wings for an hour afterward, grounding it and making it vulnerable. Its wings, membranes of translucent shadow threaded with magenta lightning, allow it to fly at terrifying speeds, but each beat drains its stamina, forcing it to land after ten minutes of sustained flight.

The backstory of their meeting is carved into both their souls. A century ago, X‑abar fled into the Abyss and found Malphas chained to a pillar of screaming bone, left to starve by a demon lord who had grown bored of it. The hellhound had already eaten one of its own hind legs to survive. X‑abar did not free it out of pity. He knelt before the beast, offered his own bleeding forearm, and said, "Eat. Then we kill the one who did this." Malphas bit him to the bone, drank his violet blood, and the pact was sealed. They hunted the demon lord for forty days, and when they finally tore him apart, Malphas ate his heart while X‑abar watched, expressionless.

In typical behaviour, Malphas is unnervingly still. It can stand motionless for hours, its four amber eyes tracking movement, its third eye half‑closed like a camera aperture. It refuses to sleep unless X‑abar is also resting, and even then it keeps one eye open. It has a habit of scraping its obsidian spinal spikes against stone walls, leaving grooves that spell out the names of enemies it has killed—a tally it updates obsessively. It drinks water only if it is stagnant and warm, and it has never been seen defecating, leading some scholars to believe it transmutes waste directly into shadow energy.

When fighting alongside X‑abar, Malphas uses its incorporeal form to flank and confuse, appearing and disappearing like a nightmare stutter. It targets spellcasters first, using its Soul Howl to disrupt incantations, then goes for the hamstrings of heavy infantry. It never kills an enemy that X‑abar has marked for his own blade, understanding the unspoken hierarchy of their partnership. If X‑abar is overwhelmed, Malphas will physically interpose its body, absorbing blows that would shatter stone, its smoldering hide smoking and cracking but holding firm.

The emotional bond between master and mount is telepathic and absolute. They do not need words; a shift in X‑abar’s posture, a flick of Malphas’s tail, and they move in perfect sync. When X‑abar suffers from the aging effects of his Void Fracture, Malphas curls around him and does not move for days, its third eye projecting soothing darkness directly into his mind. In return, X‑abar has promised Malphas that when the world is finally remade, the hellhound will be given dominion over the first new moon—a kingdom of perpetual twilight where it can hunt forever.

**Section 3: Summarisation of the Soul Reaver**

The Soul Reaver is a greatsword that denies the concept of holy craftsmanship. Its type is a "void‑forged executioner's blade," measuring five feet from pommel to tip, with a blade that is neither straight nor curved but warped in a subtle, disquieting spiral, as if the metal remembers being molten and resents being cooled. Its powers are drawn from the deaths it has consumed. Each enemy slain by the Soul Reaver has a fragment of their consciousness trapped within the jagged magenta fissure that runs along the fuller; the sword can release these fragments as screaming phantoms that attack the wielder's enemies for thirty seconds before dissolving. The activation cost is that the wielder experiences the death of each released phantom simultaneously—a cascade of pain that leaves X‑abar’s nose bleeding and his hands shaking for a full minute afterward.

The backstory of the weapon is one of deliberate sacrilege. X‑abar forged it not in a traditional smithy but in the heart of a dying star he reached by tearing a hole in reality with his own bare hands. He used the broken shards of the celestial sigil he had shattered in the Cathedral of Ashen Bells as the base material, then folded them a thousand times with strands of his own hair and the blood of the first demon he ever killed. The blade was quenched in the tears of an archangel he captured and tortured into weeping. The result is a weapon that is alive in the way a tumor is alive: hungry, sentient, and malignant. It whispers to X‑abar when he sleeps, suggesting ever more creative methods of execution.

In its typical behaviour, the Soul Reaver hums constantly, a low B‑flat that vibrates through the hilt and into the wielder's bones. When enemies are near, the hum rises in pitch and the magenta fissure glows brighter, pulsing like a heartbeat. It feels heavy in the hand of anyone who is not X‑abar, as if the blade itself is judging and finding them unworthy. It has been known to twist slightly in mid‑swing to correct a poor angle, a sign of its rudimentary intelligence. On the anniversary of its forging, the blade weeps a single drop of black oil from each of the tiny eyes set into the crossguard’s skeletal demon fingers.

The fighting style the Soul Reaver enables is one of overwhelming, singular strikes. X‑abar does not use it for fencing or quick jabs; the blade is too heavy and too alive for that. Instead, he employs a two‑handed, overhand grip, using the weapon's weight to build momentum for devastating chops and cleaves. He can also plant the tip in the ground and use the hilt as a fulcrum to launch himself into the air, a technique he calls the "Crescent Descent," bringing the blade down in a vertical arc that splits armor and flesh alike. The sword's unique spiral edge means that even a glancing blow tears a curved wound that is almost impossible to stitch closed.

The colorization of the Soul Reaver is meticulous. The blade itself is a chaotic swirl of deep purple and obsidian black, like a nebula captured in glass. The jagged fissure along the fuller glows with a pulsating magenta light that shifts to crimson when the sword has recently fed. The crossguard is formed from interlocking skeletal demon fingers, each knuckle fused in a grotesque mockery of prayer; the bones are a bleached, sickly yellow, and each fingertip is tipped with a tiny, weeping eye that leaks shadows. The eyes have irises of pale green, and the tears are viscous and black, leaving stains that never dry. The hilt is wrapped in the tanned hide of a fallen angel—pale gold in color, with faint feather‑pattern scars visible under close inspection. The grip shows indentations of X‑abar’s fingers, worn deep into the leather, and the pommel is a chunk of raw, uncut soul‑stone, identical to the crystal in his sternum, jagged and sharp enough to be used as a bludgeon in close quarters. The entire weapon is warm to the touch, even in freezing conditions, and the air around it shimmers with a faint heat haze.

**Section 4: Thank You Note with Creative Dialogue**

"Your mercy is the silence between heartbeats—listen closely, it's already over."

"I did not fall. I climbed down, and the light was too afraid to follow."

"Pray to your gods. I'll wait. They never answer, but I always do."

"The scar on my brow is my brother’s last gift. I treasure it more than any crown."

"Malphas, eat the heart. Leave the screams for me."

"You mistake my stillness for patience. I am merely deciding which part of you dies last."

"There is no hell waiting for you. I am the hell, and I am already here."

"Once, I begged for salvation. Now I demand your surrender. Which do you think frightens me more?"

"The Soul Reaver is not thirsty. It is famished. And you, little one, are a single drop of rain."

"When the last light dies and the new moon rises, I will sit on a throne of your broken oaths and finally rest."

Dear VVitch X‑abar, Demon King and shattered brother,

I have written you a thousand times in my head and erased every draft. How do you thank a being who has made peace with becoming the monster the world needed? You did not ask for your fall—you chose it, and that choice has cost you every sunrise, every laugh shared over watered wine, every moment of simple, unburdened breathing. You carry the weight of a universe you intend to unmake, and yet you pause to sharpen your blade with a saint’s femur, to pat Malphas’s third eye before battle, to count strokes in a dead language that only you remember. There is a tenderness in your ritual that you would never admit to, and it is that hidden softness—the shard of the holy hunter you used to be—that makes you not a monster but a tragedy.

You have taught me that darkness is not the absence of light but a different kind of fire. You have shown me that loyalty can exist without warmth, and that a pact sealed in blood and shared hunger is more honest than any vow spoken before an indifferent altar. I thank you for your silence, for the way you let your actions speak in cleaves and shadow‑steps, for the dignity you afford your enemies by killing them quickly (most of them, anyway). I thank Malphas for its patience and its terrible, beautiful third eye. And I thank the Soul Reaver for its humming, which has become the lullaby of my own darker dreams.

May the world you build from the ashes be worthy of the price you paid. And may you, one day, find a stillness that is not the prelude to slaughter, but simply rest.

With ash and gratitude,
The one who watched from the shadows

