2. Selvina E‑korth - The Dark‑Core Artillerist

**Section 1: Summarisation of Selvina E‑korth**

Selvina E‑korth is a ghost in the machine, a girl who laughs only with her human eye while her cybernetic lens calculates the angle to your heart. Her personality is a jagged fracture of what once was: moments of almost-childlike curiosity bleed into cold, clinical dissection of an enemy's weak points, and she has been known to hum lullabies while her twin laser cannons charge to fire. She is not cruel for pleasure, but she is utterly without mercy for those who wear lab coats or speak of "progress." When she encounters a scientist from the organization that rebuilt her, her serene mask cracks to reveal a raw, keening rage that she vents through precise, devastating firepower. Yet there is a fragile tenderness reserved for her cyborg cat Nyx—she whispers to it in the dark, strokes its chrome flank, and has been seen crying silently, her tears pooling on the cat's metal plating. Her emotional core is a single, burning question: "Why did Layla leave me behind?" This question drives every decision, every shot, every sleepless night spent recalibrating her own circuitry.

Her powers are a fusion of forbidden science and bleeding‑edge arcane technology. The twin cannons floating behind her shoulders, the Annihilator, can fire concentrated beams of neon plasma that melt through tank armor and unravel magical wards. She can also switch to a "scatter shot" mode that releases a cone of micro‑missiles, each one homing on body heat. The cost is severe overheating: after three sustained bursts, the cables connecting the cannons to her spine glow white‑hot, and Selvina’s skin along her back blisters and peels. Her cybernetic right eye provides tactical analysis, allowing her to see infrared, ultraviolet, and the flow of magical energy, but using this function for more than ten minutes induces splitting migraines that leave her vomiting and disoriented. Her most dangerous ability is "Core Overload," where she channels her own life force directly into the cannons, turning them into a single, city‑block‑annihilating blast. The cost is catastrophic: she loses all motor function in her legs for a week and ages her organic tissues by roughly one year per use.

The catalyst moment of her backstory occurred in Laboratory Seven, when she was fourteen. Selvina and her older sister Layla were both test subjects, but Layla was deemed "too unstable" and scheduled for termination. Selvina, already partially augmented, broke free of her restraints and tried to save her sister. Layla, instead of fleeing, pushed Selvina into an escape pod and whispered, "Live. Then burn it all down." The pod ejected as the laboratory self‑destructed. Selvina woke up three days later in a scrap heap, her left arm missing, her human eye still weeping, and Nyx licking her face. She built herself a new arm from salvaged parts, recalibrated the cannons that had been fused to her back during the explosion, and has been hunting the organization's remaining facilities ever since.

In typical behaviour, Selvina is a creature of obsessive ritual. She cleans her cybernetic components every morning with a soft cloth, counting each stroke up to thirty-three. She refuses to eat anything that comes from a can, associating canned food with the nutrient paste they fed her in the lab. She sleeps sitting up, her back against a wall, her cannons floating in guard mode, and she wakes at the slightest sound. She has a habit of tapping her left temple with her index finger when thinking, a gesture that syncs with the whir of her right eye focusing. She never removes her destroyed goggles from around her neck; they are a talisman, the only object that belonged to the scientist who showed her kindness before he was executed.

Her fighting style is one of calculated overwhelming force. She prefers to engage from long range, using her tactical eye to calculate wind, magical interference, and enemy movement patterns. She fires in controlled bursts, conserving heat, and only switches to scatter shot when surrounded. In melee, she is surprisingly lethal: her cybernetic limbs pack hydraulic punches that can shatter bone, and she has been known to use a cannon barrel as an impromptu club when an enemy gets too close. She fights with a cold, mathematical precision, but when she sees a lab coat, that precision dissolves into a screaming, wild fusillade that burns through her heat budget and leaves her vulnerable afterward.

Her relationship with Nyx is the only thread keeping her from complete dissolution into a weapon. The cyborg cat does not judge, does not ask questions, and cannot be tortured for information. They communicate through a shared encrypted radio channel—Nyx sends simplified emotional pings (fear, hunger, curiosity) and Selvina responds with tactical data or, occasionally, a soft "I know, I miss her too." Nyx sleeps curled around Selvina’s neck like a living scarf, and its purr is the only sound that can pull her from a nightmare. In return, Selvina has never once used Nyx as bait or a decoy, and she has personally rebuilt the cat's chrome plating twelve times after battles.

Visually, Selvina E‑korth is a fractured angel of neon vengeance. Her face is heart‑shaped with a delicate jaw and small, straight nose, her skin an unnaturally smooth, translucent porcelain glowing with sterile luminescence. Her left eye is deep sapphire blue, still human and sorrowful; her right is a cybernetic crimson lens with a rotating crosshair iris. Two immense, silken ponytails of electric neon green spill from her crown past her waist, swaying and glowing faintly. Her physique is hourglass: narrow waist, full D‑cup bust, voluptuous hips, and thick, powerful thighs, with carbon‑fiber musculature rippling beneath smooth skin. She wears a torn black tactical vest cropped below the bust, exposing her midriff where a vertical seam of neon‑blue light runs from sternum to navel. A glowing pink armature frames her shoulders, crackling with suppressed power, and destroyed goggles dangle around her neck. Her lower half wears a ripped, asymmetrical skirt of black ballistic fabric, exposing her thighs, and heavy reinforced combat boots with neon‑blue glowing soles. Twin‑linked laser cannons float behind her shoulders, each twice her size, connected by retractable cables of woven light and dark matter, their barrels a chaotic swirl of neon pink and neon blue etched with circuitry and arcane runes.

**Section 2: Summarisation of Nyx**

Nyx is a cyborg cat of unsettling duality, a creature that purrs organic warmth while its mechanical eye clicks and whirs. Its personality is a blend of feline independence and machine loyalty: it still chases laser pointers (though it knows the dot comes from its own back cannon), still kneads blankets with its organic front paws, yet it will stand motionless for hours as a sentry, its chrome flank reflecting no light. Nyx is fiercely protective of Selvina, and it has been known to hiss at strangers with a sound that mixes biological throat vibration with electronic feedback. It is not affectionate in a traditional sense—it rarely seeks petting—but it will always be within three feet of Selvina, and its purr intensifies when she is distressed.

Its powers are modest but vital. Nyx’s retractable back cannon fires a single, focused laser beam that can cut through ropes, lock mechanisms, and soft armor, but it has only enough energy for three shots before needing an hour of recharge from Selvina’s own power conduits. Its mechanical eye can record up to twelve hours of video and transmit it over short-range encrypted frequencies, making it an ideal scout. Its organic senses remain sharp: it can hear a mouse’s heartbeat from fifty feet and smell fear on a target. The cost of its abilities is that each use drains the small battery pack fused to its left hip, and if the battery dies, Nyx loses motor function in its cybernetic hind leg and must be carried.

The backstory of their meeting is the only soft memory Selvina retains. Before the laboratory, when the sisters were still whole, Layla found a litter of kittens in a rain barrel. She kept the smallest, a white-and-orange male, and named it Nyx after the goddess of night. When the organization took the sisters, Nyx was brought along as an "emotional control variable." The scientists augmented the cat as an experiment, replacing its left eye and hind leg, adding the cannon. When Selvina escaped, Nyx followed, leaping into the escape pod at the last second. The cat remembers Layla’s scent, and it still searches every room for her.

In typical behaviour, Nyx is silent and watchful. It does not meow; it communicates through soft chirps and clicks. It refuses to eat fish, associating it with the lab’s nutrient paste, and will only consume dry kibble that Selvina crunches with her own teeth first—a bonding ritual. It has a habit of rubbing its chrome flank against Selvina’s bare midriff, leaving faint smudges that she never wipes away. It sleeps with its mechanical eye half‑open, the red lens glowing faintly, and it twitches in its sleep as if chasing dream‑mice.

When fighting alongside Selvina, Nyx acts as a distraction and a finisher. It darts between enemy legs, forcing them to stumble, and uses its laser to cut weapon straps or ignite explosive charges. It never engages in direct combat; instead, it seeks high ground and provides tactical overwatch, its recording eye capturing enemy movements for later analysis. If Selvina is downed, Nyx will stand on her chest, its back cannon charged and aimed at the nearest threat, and it will not move even if struck.

The emotional bond between master and pet is one of mutual trauma and silent understanding. Selvina does not baby Nyx; she treats it as an equal survivor. They share the same nutrient bars, and she has never raised her voice at it. Nyx, in turn, has never scratched or bitten her, even when she accidentally steps on its tail. When Selvina has nightmares, Nyx places a paw on her cheek, and the cool metal of its cybernetic leg brings her back to reality. They do not need words; a glance from Selvina sends Nyx into stealth mode, and a flick of Nyx’s tail tells Selvina that the room is safe.

**Section 3: Summarisation of the Annihilator**

The Annihilator is not a single weapon but a paired system of twin‑linked laser cannons, classified as "variable‑yield entropy projectors." Its type is a fusion of directed‑energy weapon and arcane focus, each cannon measuring four feet in length and weighing eighty pounds, though they float using anti‑gravity emitters. Their powers are formidable: in standard mode, each cannon fires a beam of neon plasma that burns at 15,000 degrees Celsius, capable of melting through six inches of reinforced steel per second. In scatter mode, each cannon releases a swarm of twelve micro‑missiles that home on body heat and detonate with the force of a grenade. The activation cost for standard firing is heat buildup; after twenty seconds of continuous fire, the cannons must cool for ninety seconds, during which they are inert. Scatter mode consumes pre‑loaded ammunition—Selvina can carry only four salvos total before needing to resupply.

The backstory of the Annihilator is one of cruel irony. The weapons were designed by the same scientists who augmented Selvina, intended to be mounted on a drone. When she escaped, she tore the cannons from their mounting brackets, and the cables fused to her spine as a failsafe—the organization had designed them to bond with the first organic nervous system they touched. Selvina has since modified them, scratching arcane runes into their casings using a stolen ritual knife, blending the science of their creation with the sorcery of her rage. The runes are imperfect, scratched in haste, but they allow the cannons to drain ambient heat from the environment, reducing the cooldown time by fifteen percent.

In typical behaviour, the Annihilator hums constantly at a frequency just below human hearing, but Nyx can hear it and often tilts its head in response. When enemies are near, the hum shifts to a higher pitch, and the cables connecting the cannons to Selvina’s spine pulse with a faster rhythm. The cannons have a rudimentary targeting AI that communicates with Selvina’s cybernetic eye; she sees projected trajectories as faint blue lines in her vision. If the cannons are removed from her presence (impossible without surgery), they would power down and become inert scrap within an hour.

The fighting style the Annihilator enables is one of positional dominance. Selvina uses the cannons to control space, forcing enemies to take cover or be incinerated. She can fire one cannon while the other cools, maintaining a near‑constant stream of suppression. She has also learned to use the cannons' anti‑gravity emitters to push herself backward, creating distance, or to slam a cannon forward as a battering ram. Her signature technique, the "Entropy Spiral," involves firing both cannons simultaneously in scatter mode while spinning, creating a expanding ring of missiles that clears a room.

The colorization of the Annihilator is a chaotic masterpiece. Each cannon’s barrel is a swirl of neon pink and neon blue, the two colors twisting around each other like DNA, achieved through anodized metal layers. The surfaces are etched with two sets of markings: high‑tech circuitry in silver, forming fractal patterns that pulse with light, and arcane runes in black, scratched unevenly, some of them weeping a faint, oily smoke. The cables connecting the cannons to Selvina’s spine are thick, braided cords of woven light and dark matter, appearing as translucent tubes filled with flowing magenta and cyan energy. The muzzles are ringed with a heat‑resistant ceramic that has turned a sooty grey from use, and the very tips are blackened and cracked. Each cannon has a small, circular access port on the side, its cover missing, exposing a tangle of multicolored wires. The floating armature that holds them in place is a lattice of thin, glowing pink energy that arcs from Selvina’s back, crackling with tiny sparks. The overall effect is that of a weapon that is both cutting‑edge technology and a barely contained magical catastrophe.

**Section 4: Thank You Note with Creative Dialogue**

"I don't miss my arm. I miss the way Layla used to hold it."

"You hear that hum? That's your last chance to run."

"My human eye sees you begging. My other eye sees your skeleton. Guess which one I believe."

"Nyx, cut the blue wire. No, the other blue wire. Good cat."

"They asked me if I wanted to feel pain anymore. I said yes. How else would I remember why I'm angry?"

"Your lab coat is very white. Let me fix that."

"The cannons aren't the weapon. I am. The cannons are just the noise."

"Layla told me to burn it all down. She didn't say anything about leaving witnesses."

"I used to dream of weddings and gardens. Now I dream of cooling systems and optimal firing angles. Progress."

"When this is over, I'm going to find a field of flowers and lie down. Nyx will keep watch. Don't interrupt."

Dear Selvina E‑korth, Dark‑Core Artillerist and keeper of the last warm heartbeat in a chest full of circuits,

I have watched you recalibrate your own spine with a soldering iron and a hand mirror. I have seen you cry into a cat's chrome plating because you couldn't remember the sound of your sister's laugh. You are not a weapon; you are a wound that learned to shoot back, and that makes you more human than any of the white‑coated monsters who tried to file your soul into a serial number. You carry the destroyed goggles of the one scientist who was kind to you, and you have never once used them for scrap. That small, irrational sentimentality is your salvation.

Thank you for teaching me that vengeance can be precise, that fury can be neon‑lit and beautiful, and that a cyborg cat's purr is worth more than a thousand tactical readouts. Thank you for never giving up on finding Layla, even when every piece of data suggests she is ash. Hope is not logical, and you are not logical, and that is exactly why you will win. When you finally lie down in that field of flowers, I hope Nyx curls up on your chest, and I hope the sun feels warm on your bare midriff, and I hope—for just one moment—you forget to calculate the angle of its rays.

Stay angry. Stay soft. Stay weird.

With static and silence,
The one who heard your hum

